04315nam a22005175i 9780774854559DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071998xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748545597 a10.59962/97807748545592doi  a(DE-B1597)662228  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1095.K5bP67 1998 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.9/11 aPorsild, Charlene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGamblers and Dreamers :bWomen, Men, and Community in the Klondike /cCharlene Porsild. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (264 p.) :bOver 120 b&w and colour figures and tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations, Maps, and Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tGamblers of a Hundred Hells and Dreamers from the Seven Seas -- tThe Original Yukoners and the Klondike Gold Rush -- tThe Thrill of the Chase: Miners and Other Labouring People in Dawson -- tThe Scarlet Ladder: Work and Social Life in Dawson’s Underworld -- t‘Like Flocks of Migrating Geese’: Social Work and Religious Life in the Klondike -- tSterling Reputations and Golden Opportunities: The Professional and Business Sectors of Dawson -- tWomen, Men, and Community in the Klondike -- tAppendix: Quantifying the Klondike -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe popular image of the Klondike is of a rush of white, male adventurers who overcame great physical and geographical obstacles in their quest for gold. Young, white, single American men carried forward the ideals and structures of the western frontier. It was a man's world made respectable only after the turn of the century with the arrival of white, middle class women who miraculously swept out the corners of dirt and vice and 'civilized' the society. These impressions endure despite recent attempts to correct them. Gamblers and Dreamers tackles some of the myths about the history of the North in the era of the gold rush. Though many inhabitants came and went, Charlene Porsild focuses on the concept of community commitment to show that many put down roots. This in-depth study of Dawson City at the turn of the century reveals that the city had a cosmopolitan character, a stratified society, and a definite permanence. It examines the lives of First Nations peoples, miners and other labourers, professionals, merchants, dance hall performers and sex trade workers, providing fascinating detail about those who left homes and jobs to strike it rich in the last great gold rush of the nineteenth century. In the process, Gamblers and Dreamers puts a human face on this compelling period of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485455940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774854559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774854559/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles